{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Authenticated identity — entity + authorship certification + provider-neutral user mapping\n\n## Context\nrebar has no real concept of **who** performed an operation: `author` is `git config user.name`, an\nunauthenticated free string anyone with push access to `origin/tickets` can forge. Two needs follow:\n(1) attribute ticket events to a **real person** so activity is auditable and non-repudiable, and\n(2) map that person to **external ticket-system users** (Jira now; GitHub Issues / Linear later) so\nsync assigns work to the right person. **Beneficiary:** projects syncing to external trackers (correct\nassignee/reporter attribution, wrong or lost today) and anyone auditing \"who did this.\" This epic\ndepends on the **asymmetric attestation foundation** for its signing substrate.\n\n## Approach (and why)\nAdopt **git-bug's** identity model on rebar's existing event machinery, filling its gaps:\n- **Identity = a first-class entity** whose event log IS its version chain (rebar already has\n  event-sourcing / replay / snapshot). Stable **opaque rebar id** as the handle — **not**\n  self-certifying; the signing key provides tamper-evidence, not the id. Attributes: `name`, `email`,\n  `{provider, external_id}` external mappings, and **public** keys only.\n- **Attribution always** (name+email denormalized on every event, git-style) + an optional\n  `author_id` reference + an optional **authorship signature** — a new attestation kind on the\n  foundation's substrate (namespace `rebar.authorship.v1`).\n- **Trust root = the identity's in-band public keys**, TOFU on the genesis key + **G2** (key add/\n  rotate/revoke must be signed by a currently-valid key). Safe for authorship: low authority, cannot\n  forge another person's signatures; the worst case from a bad TOFU binding is a display-name dispute.\n- **Provider-neutral mapping.** `{provider, external_id}` keys on the provider's **opaque stable id**,\n  never email. Jira is the **first adapter** behind a provider seam; an unmapped inbound user mints a\n  **placeholder** that idempotently auto-upgrades.\n- **Deliberate creation.** A normal write never auto-mints an identity **entity**; identities are\n  created explicitly or as a mapping target (see the default-install invariant below).\n\n## Mechanisms (concrete definitions — these resolve the load-bearing terms)\n- **Private key material.** Authorship signing uses the developer's **existing SSH private key** via\n  `ssh-agent` / `~/.ssh`; it is **never** stored in the repo or on the `tickets` branch. The identity\n  entity stores only **public** keys, and a write-time guard rejects any attempt to place private-key\n  material into an identity event.\n- **Era (key-validity window).** \"Era\" is a position in the **append-only, reconverged order of the\n  `tickets` branch**, not wall-clock. Each key record on the identity carries\n  `{pubkey, valid_from_seq, valid_to_seq}`, where `seq` is the merged-log sequence index derived from\n  rebar's existing HLC/Lamport event ordering (the same ordering git-bug's `ValidKeysAtTime` uses,\n  scoped to log position). An event verifies against the keys whose `[valid_from_seq, valid_to_seq)`\n  window contains that event's merged-log `seq`. Because the reconcile/merge order is deterministic\n  once merged, all clones agree post-merge; pre-merge a clone uses its provisional local order and the\n  authoritative check (the merge gate) runs on the merged order.\n- **Verification state (exhaustive enum).** `show`/`fsck` surface exactly one of:\n  `verified` (a valid signature by an in-band key whose era window contains the event),\n  `unsigned` (no authorship signature present),\n  `unverified` (a signature is present but fails — unknown/foreign key, tampered bytes, or a key not\n  valid at the event's era). Schema location: the `fsck` report entry + `show` output.\n- **The \"merge gate\" (the real control).** rebar's `tickets` branch auto-pushes to `origin/tickets`\n  with no GitHub pre-receive hook, so enforcement is a **CI verification job** — a GitHub Actions\n  workflow on the `tickets` branch that runs `rebar verify-identity` / `fsck` over the **merged** log\n  and **fails the check** (non-zero exit + a structured per-event report → red commit status / alert)\n  on any `unsigned`/`unverified` event **when** the project sets `identity.require_authenticated=true`.\n  This is **detect-and-fail-on-the-merged-log**, not pre-receive rejection (the honest limitation of a\n  hookless remote); the local write-gate is only a fast-fail UX affordance. Deployment prerequisite:\n  enable the workflow **and** set the config key.\n- **Authorship DSSE envelope.** payloadType `rebar.authorship.v1`; the DSSE `subject` binds the signed\n  event by `{event uuid, event content-hash}` so a signature cannot be lifted to another event. If the\n  signing key is unavailable at write time, the event is authored **unsigned** (Tier 0) — the write\n  never blocks.\n- **Placeholder create-path.** The identity create path supports **system-minted placeholders** (no\n  user present, no keys, partial data): `create_placeholder(provider, external_id, display_name)`,\n  owned by the entity child and consumed by the inbound-ghost child.\n- **Modify-Reporter constraint.** Setting the Jira `reporter` field via REST requires the project's\n  Jira role to hold the **\"Modify Reporter\"** permission; without it, reporter sync degrades to\n  assignee-only (documented), never hard-fails.\n- **Default-install invariant.** With zero identity configuration, behavior is byte-identical to\n  pre-feature: a write succeeds with the denormalized git author (name+email — this is the git commit\n  author, already public in commit metadata, so it is **not** new email exposure; the \"no broadcast\"\n  property is specifically that **no identity entity with keys/mappings is auto-minted** by a normal\n  write), and `list`/`ready`/gates behave identically.\n\n## Scope\n- **In:** the `identity` entity (a new ticket-type on the `session_log` exemption pattern); event\n  attribution fields; the authorship attestation kind on the foundation's substrate; the TOFU + G2 key\n  chain with era-scoped validity; the provider-neutral mapping + Jira adapter + placeholder/auto-upgrade;\n  reconciler outbound assignee/reporter + inbound ghost; opt-in enforcement (local write-gate + the CI\n  merge-gate verify job + fsck marking); snapshot/compaction carrying folded identities + signatures;\n  docs + ADR.\n- **Out:** the signing substrate itself (foundation epic); operation-cert behavior (op-cert epic);\n  DSSE transparency-log / keyless follow-ons; **actual** GitHub Issues / Linear sync (the adapter seam\n  must not preclude them, but wiring them is separate).\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A person running rebar has a modeled identity; events attribute it (name+email always; an authorship\n  signature when opted in), verified offline against the identity's keys.\n- An opt-in project can REQUIRE authenticated authorship: `unsigned`/`unverified` events are flagged by\n  fsck and fail the CI merge-gate check, while replay never rejects (availability preserved).\n- The identity provides a stable local↔`accountId` map the reconciler uses to set the Jira assignee\n  (and reporter where the Modify-Reporter permission is held), degrading gracefully when `accountId`\n  can't be resolved; unmapped inbound Jira users become auto-upgrading placeholders.\n- Key rotation works: events verify against the keys whose era window contains them; a revoked key\n  cannot sign new events.\n- Default install is byte-identical to pre-feature; signing and enforcement are fully opt-in.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A new `identity` ticket-type exists and is exempt from lifecycle / gates / graph / Jira-sync\n      (mirrors `session_log`); a create path mints one carrying name, email, `{provider,external_id}`\n      mappings, and **public** keys, and a `create_placeholder(provider, external_id, display_name)`\n      path mints a keyless partial-data placeholder. Verified by creating both, asserting `show`\n      renders the fields, and asserting exclusion from `ready`/`next_batch`/default `list`.\n- [ ] Every mutating event carries a denormalized `author` name + email; an optional `author_id`\n      references an identity. Regression test: existing events without `author_id`/email still replay\n      to the same state.\n- [ ] An `authorship` kind (payloadType `rebar.authorship.v1`) signs the event's DSSE-PAE bytes via the\n      foundation substrate, with the DSSE `subject` binding `{event uuid, event content-hash}`, and\n      verifies offline against the identity's in-band keys; a test asserts an event signed by identity A\n      does not verify against B, a tampered event fails, and an unavailable signing key yields an\n      `unsigned` (Tier-0) write, never a blocked write.\n- [ ] Each identity key record carries `{pubkey, valid_from_seq, valid_to_seq}` (merged-log seq); key\n      add/rotate/revoke is refused unless signed by a currently-valid key (G2). A test asserts an\n      unsigned key-add is refused, and an event whose merged-log `seq` falls outside a key's\n      `[valid_from_seq, valid_to_seq)` fails while one inside passes.\n- [ ] `{provider, external_id}` mappings key on the provider's opaque id; the reconciler resolves an\n      outbound Jira assignee by `accountId`, bootstraps via `/user/search` best-effort, and degrades to\n      project-default (`-1`)/unassigned without hard-failing when email is hidden; reporter is set by\n      `accountId` only when the Modify-Reporter permission is held, else assignee-only. Test with a\n      fixture identity + stubbed `accountId`.\n- [ ] An inbound Jira user with no mapping creates a placeholder via `create_placeholder`; re-running\n      resolution after a real mapping is added idempotently upgrades it — a test asserts one identity\n      results, not two.\n- [ ] Enforcement is opt-in (`identity.require_authenticated`): with it on, a CI merge-gate job runs\n      `rebar fsck`/`verify-identity` over the merged log and **exits non-zero with a structured\n      per-event report entry** naming each `unsigned`/`unverified` event (test asserts exit code +\n      report entry); the local write-gate fails fast but is documented UX-only. Replay never rejects\n      (test: a bad-signature event still folds into state); `show`/`fsck` surface exactly one of\n      `verified`/`unverified`/`unsigned`.\n- [ ] Default-install regression: with zero identity configuration, an integration test asserts a\n      normal write succeeds unsigned, **no identity entity is minted**, and `list`/`ready`/gates behave\n      identically to pre-feature (proves SC \"default install unchanged\").\n- [ ] Snapshots (compaction) carry folded-event identities + signatures so compacted signed events\n      still verify (round-trip test).\n- [ ] Docs + ADR: identity model; the `verified/unverified/unsigned` enum; opt-in enforcement + the\n      CI-merge-gate-is-the-control caveat + its detect-vs-reject limitation; Jira `accountId` mapping +\n      the Modify-Reporter permission requirement; key-rotation / era (`valid_from_seq`/`valid_to_seq`);\n      private-key storage (ssh-agent/`~/.ssh`, never committed); the provider-neutral seam.\n\n## Intended decomposition (children)\n1. `identity` ticket-type + entity (attributes, **public**-key-only storage + private-key guard,\n   exemptions, normal + `create_placeholder` paths, config pointer, default-install invariant).\n2. Event attribution (name+email + `author_id`) + replay back-compat + default-install regression test.\n3. Authorship attestation kind on the foundation substrate (DSSE subject binding; unsigned fallback).\n4. TOFU genesis + G2 signed key-rotation chain + era (`valid_from_seq`/`valid_to_seq`) validity.\n5. Provider-neutral mapping + Jira adapter (outbound assignee/reporter, Modify-Reporter degrade).\n6. Inbound ghost/placeholder + idempotent auto-upgrade.\n7. Opt-in enforcement: local write-gate + **CI merge-gate verify job** + fsck `verified/unverified/unsigned`\n   marking + replay-never-rejects + snapshot carries identities/sigs.\n8. Docs + ADR.\n\n## Prior art / grounding\ngit-bug identity entity + `ValidKeysAtTime` (log-position key validity) + bridge metadata; SCIM\n`externalId`; OIDC `(iss,sub)` (email disqualified as key); Jira Cloud GDPR `accountId` (email\nnull/hidden) + Modify-Reporter permission; Gitea/GitLab placeholder-user + auto-upgrade; git `.mailmap`\n(email as adopt-heuristic only). Depends on the asymmetric attestation foundation."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783739386392843001,"uuid":"8956fd77-a24c-4a90-92b0-162e833cc481"}